iOne characteristic of NixOS is that all binary applications and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilibraries are stored in `/nix/store` directory and managed by Nix		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipackage manager. This means that NixOS doesn't conform to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[the FHS standard of Linux](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Filesystem_Hierarchy_Standard),		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iand there's not even a dynamic library loader like		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i`ld-linux-x86-64.so.2` in `/lib` or `/lib64`, let alone other shared		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilibraries like `libc.so`. Therefore, unless the program is statically		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilinked, binaries compiled for other Linux distros will not run on		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iNixOS at all.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iTherefore, to use a program not packaged in Nixpkgs yet on NixOS, the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ibest way is to package it yourself by writing a packaging script in		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iNix, and add the package definition to `configuration.nix`, in order		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ito install it to the system.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThere are three good news and two bad news when it comes to NixOS		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipackaging. The good news are:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. Nixpkgs, ot the software repository for NixOS, provides a ton of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   functions for automation. For many open source softwares written in		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   popular programming languages (including C/C++, Python, Go,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   Node.js, Rust, etc., but not Java), you only need to call an		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   existing function and specify the download source of the source		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   code. Nixpkgs will automatically detect the packaging system, pass		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   in correct parameters, and package it for you.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. Nixpkgs also provides existing automated solutions for binary		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   distributed software (commonly seen in closed-source software):		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - One is Autopatchelf, which automatically modifies the library		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     paths in the binary, and points them to `/nix/store`.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - The other is Bubblewrap, or `steam-run` based on Bubblewrap, that		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     can emulate an FHS-compliant environment. As the name suggests,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     `steam-run` mainly focuses on the Steam gaming platform and the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     games on it, but it can also be used for other closed-source		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     software.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i3. Nix package manager run the packaging process in an isolated		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   environment. You can think of it as a Docker container, with no		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   networking access, no escalated privileges, and no access to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   filesystem except a few designated ones. All attempts to access		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   external paths or Internet will fail; the compilation can only		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   proceed with explicitly specified dependencies in the Nix packaging		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   script. Therefore, the packaged program is guaranteed to have no		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   dependency on external files.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAnd the bad news are:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. Software developers may not know Linux better than packagers.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   Developers may hardcode paths in codes and compilation scripts, and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   make assumptions that are only true in FHS compliant environments.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   When this happens, you need to write patches and fix the paths		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   yourself, so the program can correctly compile and run on NixOS.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. When, for some reason, you cannot use an existing function, you		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   need to prepare yourself for a long debugging journey:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - Developer organized the source code in a strange way (like		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     `osdlyrics`), or used a non-standard compilation procedure		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - Program actively detects its execution environment (like WeChat		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     for UOS)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - Program actively detects changes to itself (like SVP video		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     interpolation software)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iA few months ago, I replaced my daily driver distro from Arch Linux to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iNixOS, and I've packaged quite a few programs on NixOS. This post will		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iexplain the packaging procedures in NixOS as well as frequent problems		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iand solutions, starting from the easier ones.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i# Preparation		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iFirst, I strongly recommend you to install NixOS and only package on		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iNixOS.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Although you can package software with Nix on non-NixOS operating		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  systems, the produced software may still have runtime dependencies		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  on the FHS structure, causing incompatibilities on NixOS. Of course,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  if you're only packaging for yourself, and have no plan to share the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  packages, you can safely ignore this.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- In addition, you need to use		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  [Home-Manager](https://github.com/nix-community/home-manager), a		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  program that manages config files in your Home directory with a		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Nix-language config file, to install Nix-packaged software on a		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  non-NixOS system. You need to do your own research on how to use		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  this program.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## Using Packaging Template from NUR		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iNUR is a Nix software repository managed by individual users, similar		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ito AUR of Arch Linux. NUR provides a ready-to-use template that can be		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iused to centrally manage your packages.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iGo to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[nur-packages-template](https://github.com/nix-community/nur-packages-template)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ion GitHub, click "Use this template" and create a repository. You will		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
istore all your custom packages in that new repository.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> If you want to publish your packages to NUR, you need to send a Pull		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> Request to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> [NUR's main repository](https://github.com/nix-community/NUR) and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> add the URL to your own repository. However, even if you don't do		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> that, you can still use your own repository.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThen, clone your repository.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- If you don't use Nix Flake, you can run the following command to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  build the example package from the template:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ```bash		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  nix-build -A example-package		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- If you use Flake, you can run the following commands:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ```bash		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  nix flake update # Optional, update repositories in flake.lock to latest version		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  nix build ".#example-package"		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThen, add your own repository in your NixOS config.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- If you don't use Nix Flake, add the following definitions to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  `configuration.nix`:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ```nix		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  nixpkgs.config.packageOverrides = pkgs: {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    myRepo = import (builtins.fetchTarball "https://github.com/nix-community/nur-packages-template/archive/master.tar.gz") {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      inherit pkgs;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    };		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  };		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Replace `https://github.com/nix-community/nur-packages-template`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  with your repository URL.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Now you can use your own packages in the form of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  `pkgs.myRepo.example-package`.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- If you use Nix Flake, add the following definitions to the `inputs`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  section in `flake.nix`:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ```nix		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  inputs = {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    # ...		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    myRepo = {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      url = "github:nix-community/nur-packages-template";		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      inputs.nixpkgs.follows = "nixpkgs";		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    };		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    # ...		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  };		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Replace `nix-community/nur-packages-template` with your repository		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  URL.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Then, in the `output` section in `flake.nix`, for each of your		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  `nixosConfigurations` definition, add a module for the systems:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ```nix		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  outputs = { self, nixpkgs, ... }@inputs: {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    nixosConfigurations."nixos" = nixpkgs.lib.nixosSystem {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      system = "x86_64-linux";		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      modules = [		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        # Add the following lines at the beginning of modules		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        ({		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i          nixpkgs.overlays = [		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i            (final: prev: {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i              myRepo = inputs.myRepo.packages."${prev.system}";		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i            })		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i          ];		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        })		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        # Add the preceding lines at the beginning of modules		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        ./configuration.nix		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      ];		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    };		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  };		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  Now you can use your own packages in the form of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  `pkgs.myRepo.example-package`.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## Add Packages Straight to NixOS Config		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iOf course, instead of using the template from NUR, you can put your		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipackage definitions along with your NixOS config files.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAssuming you have this packaging definition as `example-package.nix`:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i(From		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i<https://github.com/nix-community/nur-packages-template/blob/master/pkgs/example-package/default.nix>)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```nix		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i{ stdenv }:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
istdenv.mkDerivation rec {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  name = "example-package-${version}";		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  version = "1.0";		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  src = ./.;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  buildPhase = "echo echo Hello World > example";		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  installPhase = "install -Dm755 example $out";		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i}		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iYou can use the `pkgs.callPackage` function to use it in		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i`configuration.nix`:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```nix		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i{ config, pkgs, ... }:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i{		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # Use this package directly		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  environment.systemPackages = [		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    (pkgs.callPackage ./example-package.nix { })		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ];		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  # Or define a constant for the package first		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  environment.systemPackages = let		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    examplePackage = pkgs.callPackage ./example-package.nix { };		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  in [		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    examplePackage		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  ];		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i}		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIf you want to build just this package, you can use the following		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icommand:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```bash		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
inix-build -E 'with import <nixpkgs> {}; callPackage ./example-package.nix {}'		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i# Phases in Packaging		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAlthough you can		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i[package directly with Nix package manager's `builtins.derivation` function](https://scrive.github.io/nix-workshop/04-derivations/04-raw-derivation.html),		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwe usually use the `stdenv.mkDerivation` function to generate a Nix		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipackage definition, since it's much easier. Contrary to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i`builtins.derivation`, `stdenv.mkDerivation` splits the packaging		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iprocess to 7 phases:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. Unpack phase		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - In this step, `stdenv.mkDerivation` automatically unpacks the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     source code archive specified by `src`. For example, if your		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     archive is in `.tar.gz` format, it automatically runs `tar xf`.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - But `stdenv.mkDerivation` doesn't recognize all archive types,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     for example `.zip`. In this case, you need to specify the unpack		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     command yourself:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     ```nix		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     nativeBuildInputs = [ unzip ];		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     unpackPhase = ''		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i       unzip $src		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     '';		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     ```		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - `stdenv.mkDerivation` requires that the source code resides in a		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     top-level folder in the archive. It automatically `cd`s into that		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     folder after unpack.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. Patch phase		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - In this step, `stdenv.mkDerivation` applies all `patches` in		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     sequential order. This can be used to fix the incompatibilities		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     between some programs and NixOS.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i3. Configure phase		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - This is equivalent to running `./configure` or `cmake`.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     `stdenv.mkDerivation` automatically detects the packaging system		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     and calls the appropriate commands, or, when no relevant config		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     files exist, automatically skips the phase.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - It's worth noting that, to use `cmake`, you need to add an		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     additional line of `nativeBuildInputs = [ cmake ];` to add CMake		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     into the packaging environment.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - You can add configuration parameters with `configureFlags` or		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     `cmakeFlags`, to enable or disable functionalities of the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     program.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i4. Build phase		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - This is equivalent to running `make`. You can specify the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     arguments to `make` with `makeFlags`.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i5. Check phase		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - This phase executes the unit tests in the source directory, to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     ensure that the program functions correctly.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - You can skip this step with `doCheck = false;`.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i6. Install phase		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - This is equivalent to running `make install`, which copies the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     compilation results to the relevant folder in Nix store.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - The whole building process happens in a temporary folder, rather		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     than in Nix store. Therefore, such a copy is necessary.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - When you specify the installation commands yourself, the target		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     path is stored in variable `$out`. `$out` can be either a		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     directory containing files, or simply a file.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i7. Fixup phase		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - This step cleans up the results in Nix store by, for example,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     stripping debug symbols.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - Autopatchelf Hook, a hook that automatically replaces `.so` paths		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     for closed-source programs, is executed in this step.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - You can disable this step with `dontFixup = true;`.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
