iSoftware packaging has always been difficult. In the packaging		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iprocess, you often need to consider all dependencies of the software,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iand try repeatedly whilst adjusting parameters. Compared to other		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
idistros, packaging in NixOS (and Nixpkgs) may seem complicated at		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifirst, but is actually easy:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Many repetitive work are automated with functions;		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- Packaging is isolated from the main OS, no worries of package		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  breaking for others because of residuals or missing dependencies.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIn this post, I demonstrated a few common packaging scenarios,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iincluding open source and closed source ones. But since I only shown a		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilimited number of examples, they certainly do not cover all scenarios		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iyou may run into, so you're likely required to do your own research:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- [NixOS Wiki](https://nixos.wiki/) provides packaging guides for many		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  popular programming languages, as well as special cases (like Qt).		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- [Nixpkgs](https://github.com/NixOS/nixpkgs) itself is a large		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  package repository with definitions for over 80,000 packages, which		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  serves as a reference.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i- [NUR](https://nur.nix-community.org/) is package repositories		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  managed by Nix users, similar to AUR.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
